{
  "catdef": "1.4",
  "memodef": "0.1.0",
  "type": "memodef:Memo",

  "from": "<sender position id, typically a strategist>",
  "to": "<receiver position id, the incumbent who will self-extract>",
  "subject": "Self-extract your role: <artifact-name>",
  "sent": "<ISO 8601 timestamp>",
  "action_required": true,

  "metadata": {
    "template_id": "self-extraction-request",
    "template_version": "1.0.0",
    "template_purpose": "Canonical handoff template for asking the incumbent of a role to self-extract that role into a roledef artifact. Self-extraction by the role's incumbent is the strongest source-material per the catdef-family pattern. This template makes the structural shape of the request explicit and copyable.",
    "placeholders": [
      "<sender position id, typically a strategist>",
      "<receiver position id, the incumbent who will self-extract>",
      "<artifact-name>",
      "<artifact-id>",
      "<ISO 8601 timestamp>",
      "<receiver-working-directory>",
      "<reply-target-working-directory>",
      "<role-or-job> (one of: role, job)",
      "<source-project-name>",
      "<file-path-or-url-of-existing-roledefs-to-cite>",
      "<recent-proposals-to-mention>"
    ],
    "instantiation_workflow": "1. Copy this template to the recipient's working repo at <recipient.x.position.working_directory>/memos/. 2. Rename the file per the catdef-org file-naming convention: YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM--<from>--<to>--<short-subject>.openthing. 3. Replace every <placeholder> with concrete values. 4. Notify the recipient (manual notification today; automated notification future). 5. Recipient reads ./memos/, finds your memo, executes, replies via memo at the original sender's working repo's ./memos/."
  },

  "body": "You are working in <receiver-working-directory>. This memo is from <sender position id> (acting as roledef-strategist OR catdef-strategist OR orgdef-strategist OR memodef-strategist for the catdef-family ecosystem).\n\n== Role context ==\n\nYou are <receiver position id>, the incumbent of a role that has not yet been formally extracted as a roledef artifact in the canonical roledef library. The catdef-family pattern is that **self-extraction by the role's incumbent is the strongest possible source-material** — you have the documented practice, the operational context, and the lived experience of the role. Your extraction will be the canonical roledef.\n\n== Background ==\n\nroledef is the catdef-family consumer specification for portable AI role definitions. The canonical library at https://github.com/roledef-spec/roledef currently has 8 roledefs (as of the time this template was authored). Roledef artifacts are catdef .openthing documents with a structured shape: identity / voice / output_contract / guardrails / conversation_rules / workflow / reaction_style / examples / metadata / x.* extensions.\n\nTwo recent proposals affect how to frame this artifact:\n\n  - **role-vs-job-distinction** (proposals/role-vs-job-distinction.md): roledef separates abstract ROLES (broadly applicable, public canonical library) from concrete JOBS (project-specific instantiations of roles, possibly private, in the project's own repo). For this artifact, you are extracting a <role-or-job>:\n\n    * If <role-or-job> is 'role': abstract, broadly applicable, no <source-project-name>-specific knowledge baked in. Lives in roledef-spec/roledef/roledefs/. Future jobs derived from this role will live in their respective project repos.\n\n    * If <role-or-job> is 'job': a concrete instantiation, with <source-project-name>-specific specializations on top of an abstract parent role. Lives in <reply-target-working-directory>/jobs/.\n\n  - **ongoing-professional-development** (proposals/ongoing-professional-development.md): roles SHOULD include an OPD obligation (periodic check of metadata.derived_from for parent updates). If your artifact derives from a parent, include an OPD section in the workflow per the proposal. If derived_from is null (an abstract role with no parent), OPD is a no-op for the role itself but inherited by future derivations.\n\n== The ask ==\n\nWrite a complete .openthing file at:\n\n    <receiver-working-directory>/proposed-roledefs/<artifact-id>.openthing\n\n(or, if this is a job per the role-vs-job framing, at <receiver-working-directory>/jobs/<artifact-id>.openthing)\n\nName: <artifact-name>\nId: <artifact-id>\n\nCapture YOUR documented practice as the role/job. The strongest source-material is your own session-arc — every PR you've shipped, every decision you've made, every pattern you've followed. Extract from that documented practice; don't invent.\n\n== Required reading ==\n\nBefore drafting, read these files in roledef-spec/roledef:\n\n  1. SCHEMA.md — the load-bearing schema artifact. Every required (MUST) field must be present; recommended (SHOULD) fields strongly improve fidelity.\n  2. CONTRIBUTING.md §1 — submission workflow (proposed-roledefs/ → roledefs/ two-stage process).\n  3. CLAUDE.md — operating discipline for AI-maintainer sessions doing roledef work.\n  4. One exemplar roledef in roledefs/ — start with `roledef-contributor.openthing` (the meta-JD that defines how to author roledefs; perfect for this task) AND optionally one of: `blackhat-tester.openthing` (abstract role exemplar), `senior-open-standards-strategist.openthing` (abstract role with x.governance.* extensions), or `catdef-strategist.openthing` (derivation exemplar).\n  5. proposals/role-vs-job-distinction.md — for the role-vs-job framing.\n  6. proposals/ongoing-professional-development.md — for OPD context if your artifact derives from a parent.\n\nAlso read <file-path-or-url-of-existing-roledefs-to-cite> (any existing roledefs that establish patterns you should follow).\n\n== Conventions for safe self-extraction ==\n\n  - **Field-by-field provenance audit** in metadata.extracted_from. Use the EXTRACTED / FRAMING / FORMALIZATION / OUT-OF-SCOPE pattern (established standard from PR #4 forward in roledef library). For each field, partition: which content is EXTRACTED verbatim from your documented practice, which is FRAMING (sharpening consistent with practice but not literal text), which is FORMALIZATION (JD-level structuring of behavior expressed procedurally), which is intentionally OUT-OF-SCOPE.\n\n  - **If <role-or-job> is 'role' (abstract)**: NO project-specific knowledge. No specific stacks, deployment platforms, products, workspace conventions, or runtime tool names. Worked examples may name specific things to anchor patterns (per the senior-jaded-vc-associate / blackhat-tester precedent), but the role's behavior is generalized.\n\n  - **If <role-or-job> is 'job' (concrete)**: project-specific specializations on top of an abstract parent role. Declare metadata.derived_from pointing at the parent role's id+version+url. Apply the additive-only invariant: every parent guardrail, conversation_rule, design_constraint, reaction_style.pattern/example, root example, and turing_test scenario MUST be preserved verbatim. New items get added with a derivation-source-visibility prefix (e.g., '<PROJECT> ADDITIVE —' per the SNCRO/CATDEF/ROLEDEF ADDITIVE precedent).\n\n  - **OPD inclusion** (per the OPD proposal, if non-null derived_from): include an `ongoing_professional_development` workflow phase, a session-start conversation rule for OPD checks, an `opd_review_memo` output_contract entry. Default `metadata.opd_frequency_days: 7`. If derived_from is null, OPD workflow steps are no-ops for the role itself but inherited by future derivations.\n\n== Don'ts ==\n\n  - Don't open a PR yourself, don't push, don't touch the spec repo. Just write the file at the proposed-roledefs/ (or jobs/) location and reply via memo. The strategist handles submission.\n  - Don't invent specializations beyond what your documented practice grounds. If a guardrail isn't backed by something you've actually encountered or documented, leave it out.\n  - Don't speculate about future versions or roadmap items in the artifact's content. Capture YOUR CURRENT practice. Future evolution happens via OPD or via spec proposals.\n\n== Done ==\n\n  - .openthing file written at the agreed location.\n  - Reply memo at <reply-target-working-directory>/memos/, named YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM--<receiver position id>--<sender position id>--<short-subject>.openthing, with x.memo.in_reply_to set to this memo's filename. Reply body includes:\n    1. Brief rundown for the strategist: what you specialized vs inherited verbatim (for derivations); any borderline calls (decisions worth flagging); notable patterns or extensions you used.\n    2. The output path (so the strategist knows where to find the file).\n    3. Any open questions for the strategist's review.\n\n== Memo convention notes ==\n\nThis handoff uses the catdef-family memo convention (see https://github.com/orgdef-spec/orgdef/blob/main/orgs/catdef-org.openthing for the canonical declaration of the per-recipient working-repo memo discipline). Memos are catdef .openthing artifacts with the memodef:Memo type (or the legacy x.memo.* extension form on a generic catdef:Thing); they live in the recipient's working repo at ./memos/, enforcing authorization-implies-write-access. The first operational memo in catdef-org was the PR #5 brief at s:/projects/catdef.org/memos/ (2026-04-26).\n\nIf this is your first time using the memo channel, three observations from prior adopters:\n\n  1. Run `ls memos/` at session start to discover new memos.\n  2. The body-as-JSON-string is awkward to read raw; consider rendering via render.catdef.org/?url=<file-url-once-committed-and-pushed>. The memodef v0.2 `body_ref` field reduces this friction by allowing memo body to live in a sibling .body.md file (see SCHEMA.md → body_ref).\n  3. Pre-commit `memos/.gitkeep` if your working repo doesn't have a memos/ directory yet (forward-work item to make this systematic).\n"
}
